Cell["\<\
I have the option today of making a SIM card contract with Lebara. 3GB/month \
per \[Sterling]5,  15GB/month per \[Sterling]10,  30GB/month per \
\[Sterling]15, or unlimited data per \[Sterling]25. I go by bus to work on a \
45min round-trip a day and during this time I watch movies by Netflix with a \
stream of SD videos with 1.5GB/hour. Assuming that I work 20 days a month, \
which contract should I make?  \
\>", "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811597558054982*^9, 3.8115976057370243`*^9}, {
  3.811598866902531*^9, 3.811598947701604*^9}, {3.873966189550556*^9, 
  3.873966290271943*^9}, {3.87396639231437*^9, 3.873966392650847*^9}, {
  3.873966543506553*^9, 3.873966702926488*^9}, {3.873966739653502*^9, 
  3.873966789731563*^9}, {3.873966958529221*^9, 3.8739669682276177`*^9}, {
  3.873967009128764*^9, 3.873967018649927*^9}, {3.8836319930558243`*^9, 
  3.883631998295511*^9}, {3.8836330742263737`*^9, 3.883633086066509*^9}, {
  3.946719908467012*^9, 
  3.946719912784012*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"542dfc13-03e0-48de-96da-\
2845923fee29"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Only for movies I will need ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"45", 
        RowBox[{"min", "/", "day"}], "*", "20", "days"}], ")"}], "/", "60"}], 
     ")"}], "hours", " ", "in", " ", "20", " ", "days"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"80de8582-5e8d-4a90-bb0e-88257c80942a"],
 "=15hours.\n15 hours*1.5GB/hours=22.5GB/month.\n\nContract would depend on \
amount required for data for other things, such as chat and browsing, but \
either the one for \[Sterling]15 or \[Sterling]25. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.87396703137049*^9, 3.8739670450491*^9}, {
  3.8739671114562483`*^9, 3.8739671498672047`*^9}, {3.873967180648045*^9, 
  3.873967245683394*^9}, {3.873967277863775*^9, 3.873967286400167*^9}, {
  3.883632900104332*^9, 3.883632924044507*^9}, {3.883632956036128*^9, 
  3.883632956692096*^9}, {3.8836329885244102`*^9, 3.8836332248494*^9}, {
  3.905231938355049*^9, 
  3.9052319393289423`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"6019a780-0e5a-4149-bca3-\
dcf0d85dcbc0"],

Cell["\<\
List at least two differences between handling structured and unstructured \
data.\
\>", "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811597558054982*^9, 3.8115976057370243`*^9}, {
  3.874729727096277*^9, 
  3.874729728164411*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"3b35e172-57e5-4617-b067-\
4e03f1fb7d64"],

Cell["\<\
Structured data is highly organized, can be seamlessly included in a database \
and readily searched via simple search operations. Easy to find information \
searched and associations among different Tables. Data stored in databases \
require a design model, or fixed schema. Structure data is akin to machine \
languages, in that it makes information much easier to be parsed by \
computers.  

Unstructured data has no underlying structure, without labels, and \
appropriate for real-world data. it is more scalable, but hard to find \
associations among documents. No design model is necessary for the storage. \
It is often the data about the human communication.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811924514531267*^9, 3.811924580509577*^9}, {
  3.811924614808731*^9, 3.811924643825737*^9}, {3.8119246881930513`*^9, 
  3.811924712973387*^9}, {3.811924747388619*^9, 3.811924757516851*^9}, {
  3.811925029933666*^9, 3.811925072884932*^9}, {3.811925407338892*^9, 
  3.811925409385319*^9}, {3.811925831403771*^9, 3.811925902601408*^9}, {
  3.905232351998042*^9, 
  3.905232359468914*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"22ba267f-7cb3-4358-828e-\
17d879ca01a2"],

Cell["Give three examples of structured data formats.", "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811597558054982*^9, 
  3.8115976393975573`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"cd082854-6f17-42fa-85a6-\
114016624ff0"],

Cell["\<\
Structured data is related and organized in tabular formats, with pre - \
defined design or schema. For example, customer data, with names and their \
addresses, student records, patient data, student class marks, etc... It can \
be stored using different  formats:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811925655591942*^9, 3.811925790486698*^9}, {
  3.8119259490544*^9, 
  3.811925953515819*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"bf82c3c0-79df-4c85-b441-\
02089ddc6cb2"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["CSV",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ": Comma-Separated Values, ",
 StyleBox["TSV",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ": Tab-separated values, Spreadsheets (e.g., Excel tables)"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811924325059143*^9, 3.811924335627767*^9}, {
   3.811924842158106*^9, 3.811924861055276*^9}, {3.811924893196906*^9, 
   3.811924895611497*^9}, {3.811925293262767*^9, 3.8119253480652122`*^9}, 
   3.8119254635206532`*^9, {3.81192565195158*^9, 3.811925653175873*^9}, 
   3.811925956201859*^9, 
   3.9773861398397617`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"37b87bfa-812c-40d3-b75d-\
8ff1059df9c5"],

Cell["Give three examples of unstructured data formats.", "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811597558054982*^9, 
  3.811597641437386*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8f93b7a6-069e-434c-b913-\
49a5e601d9b3"],

Cell["\<\
Unstructured data can found in different forms: from web pages to emails, \
from blogs to social media posts. It is data generated by people, \
governments, by text, sound, videos, emails, social media feeds, and \
multimedia content. Storage of this data use No-SQL databases.   \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8119243437743053`*^9, 3.811924348117311*^9}, {
  3.811925466917685*^9, 3.811925552853195*^9}, {3.9052323685589337`*^9, 
  3.905232385891736*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"7050d9b6-8438-47c9-83a1-\
9e25884bc99d"],

Cell["\<\
How will you convert a CSV file to a TSV file? List at least two different \
strategies. \
\>", "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811597558054982*^9, 
  3.811597683017454*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"64a7c023-0ed6-432f-a600-\
d2f51c489b5a"],

Cell["\<\
Standard text editors can do this, and also several available apps. \
Mathematica can also automatically export data types, or this can be directly \
done by replacing the comma by a < tab > delimiter. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811926079277318*^9, 3.811926084087811*^9}, {
   3.811926210115869*^9, 3.811926274146549*^9}, 3.8225742263286*^9, {
   3.873967370109357*^9, 
   3.873967372008259*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"37a22be8-756a-4765-8388-\
1366f4491604"],

Cell["\<\
You are looking at employee records. Some have no middle name, some have a \
middle initial, and others have a complete middle name. How do you explain \
such inconsistency in the data? Provide at least two explanations.   \
\>", "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811597558054982*^9, 3.811597756907136*^9}, {
  3.811931554706965*^9, 
  3.811931557783824*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"b9730cdb-408c-4fba-b018-\
a998dd0083f6"],

Cell["\<\
There are always two sources for this inconsistency. The operator \
imputing/collecting the data into the system and the user who provides the \
information. The operator can make a mistake by the input, even when the \
information about the middle name was correctly given, but some people might \
not have middle names. Whereas some others prefer not to provide information \
about the middle name. I am one of those that rarely provide my middle name, \
and when I do provide, some times I provide the initials, others I provide \
the whole middle name.   

Other reasons: lack of standardization to collect the data, evolving data \
collection practices, system migration or integration.
\t\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.811926334930008*^9, 3.811926416337001*^9}, {
  3.8119264475197678`*^9, 3.811926577030983*^9}, {3.905232459537258*^9, 
  3.9052324669512787`*^9}, {3.905232534975924*^9, 
  3.905232614521511*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"703d554b-1153-4a48-9336-\
7b3444e09da1"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

